## DESCRIPTION
## Find a regression line for data involves public teacher salaries.
## ENDDESCRIPTION

## Tagged by LD

## DBsubject(Algebra)
## DBchapter(Linear equations and functions)
## DBsection(Applications and models)
## Institution(ASU)
## Level(2)
## KEYWORDS('Statistics', 'Linear regression', 'line')

DOCUMENT();    # This should be the first executable line in the problem.

loadMacros(
    'PGstandard.pl',         'PGML.pl',
    'PGchoicemacros.pl',     'PGnumericalmacros.pl',
    'PGstatisticsmacros.pl', 'PGcourse.pl'
);

Context('Numeric')->variables->are(t => Real);

$numpoints = 11;

@year = (1990 .. 2000);

# coefficients of the polynomial
$a = random(922.05,   942.05,   .01);
$b = random(33167.68, 33207.68, .01);

$reg = Regression->new(2, "regression", [ "const", "X1" ]);

for $j (0 .. ($numpoints - 1)) {
    $exact      = $b + $a * ($year[$j] - 1990);
    $salary[$j] = random(.95 * $exact, 1.05 * $exact, 0.001);
    $salary[$j] = round($salary[$j]);

    $reg->include($salary[$j], [ 1, ($year[$j] - 1990) ]);
}

@coeff = $reg->theta();

$tab = DataTable(
    [ [ 'Year', 'Salary' ], map([ $year[$_], $salary[$_] ], 0 .. $#year) ],
    tablecss   => { border => '1px black solid' },
    allcellcss => { border => '1px black solid' }
);

$linear_model = Formula("$coeff[0][0]+$coeff[0][1]*t");

BEGIN_PGML
The table below contains the average public school classroom teacher's salaries, [`S`],        for an 11-year period.  Letting [`t = 0`] represent 1990, use a graphing utility to        find a linear model for the data.

[$tab]*

Salary, written as a function of [`t`] is given by

 [`S(t) = `] [_]{$linear_model}
END_PGML

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
To solve this problem, you should enter the data into some software (excel, google sheets, desmos, ...) that performs linear regression.  Switch the years to [`t`] that range from 0 to 10 and perform the regression.  You may need to read the help pages on the tool to do this.

The result should be

[```S(t) = [$linear_model] ```]
END_PGML_SOLUTION

ENDDOCUMENT();
